(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[96],{695:function(e,o,t){(window.__NEXT_P=window.__NEXT_P||[]).push(["/articles/conversation",function(){return t(3499)}])},3499:function(e,o,t){"use strict";t.r(o),t.d(o,{default:function(){return i}});var a=t(5893),n=t(9008);function i(){return(0,a.jsxs)("div",{children:[(0,a.jsxs)(n.default,{children:[(0,a.jsx)("title",{children:"Conversational ninja"}),(0,a.jsx)("meta",{name:"description",content:"Generated by create next app"}),(0,a.jsx)("link",{rel:"icon",href:"/favicon.ico"})]}),(0,a.jsx)("h1",{children:"Talking magically"}),(0,a.jsx)("p",{children:"I could have named this article - the art of conversation, but I would like to keep it basic and not get too flowery. The point is to not get stuck in the words too much and talk about principles and action. Now you are well versed in the concepts of body language. Now next step is to understand that when you approach someone what and how would you talk."}),(0,a.jsx)("p",{children:"Remember the most basic underlying principle of this system is demonstrating high value. Before you approach someone, you have no value. Once you make the approach, you have to immediately convert that value to a high value rather than a low value. You have learned the body language principles and body language is used to demonstrate high value. But most human interaction would be incomplete without a conversation."}),(0,a.jsx)("h2",{children:"What to talk?"}),(0,a.jsx)("p",{children:"When you enter the room, you have to read it. Is it a formal or informal occasion? What are the profession and interests of the people in that room? Are the gentry liberal or conservative? What can be their interests? Then you have to talk in accordance with that. However, most people, especially the introverted ones will still have trouble talking to the people, because of a classic issue - \"I don't know what to talk\xa0about\". Don't worry if you do the next exercise properly, within a couple of weeks you'll be a conversational ninja."}),(0,a.jsx)("h2",{children:"Exercise: Conversational ninja"}),(0,a.jsx)("p",{children:"This one exercise has changed life of many of my students, especially the introverted ones."}),(0,a.jsxs)("ol",{children:[(0,a.jsx)("li",{children:"You have to do it for 10 minutes daily"}),(0,a.jsx)("li",{children:"Switch on the selfie camera of your smartphone in the video mode or just stand in front of a mirror."}),(0,a.jsx)("li",{children:"Pick one word(noun), which can be anything like - car, tree, umbrella, or any random thing"}),(0,a.jsx)("li",{children:"Speak on it for 20 seconds"}),(0,a.jsx)("li",{children:"You can speak anything about it. For example, if the word is car - you can say that I like red cars, and I like to take them on long drives, my favorite brand of car is Jaguar, but I hate SUVs. etc etc"}),(0,a.jsx)("li",{children:"After 20-30 seconds change the topic"}),(0,a.jsx)("li",{children:"The next topic should be the word from the last sentence of the previous topic. For example, it can be Jaguar. You can say - that jaguars are founds in the rainforests of Amazon, they're from the cat family but are very ferocious. I would like to see them in the Amazon jungles."}),(0,a.jsx)("li",{children:"Continue this for 10 minutes. Do this daily and in a couple of weeks, you'll find that you'll be able to speak on any topic for a long."})]}),(0,a.jsx)("h2",{children:"Demonstrating high value through words"}),(0,a.jsx)("p",{children:"Now you know how to read the room and how to talk. So when you enter a room and read it you have to approach anyone you like, they may be the waiter there or the most important person there. It doesn't matter. The point is, as soon as you enter the venue, your main focus should be initiating a conversation with someone. Choose a person, make a genuine observation about them, and with a genuine interest and friendliness make the approach."}),(0,a.jsx)("p",{children:"Since your intention is to grow your professional network, it's better to make an observation related to their professional (and not personal) behavior or achievement, and then begin the conversation with that. For example, you see the CEO of a company standing across the room, you have an idea, if possible take out your phone go to the breakout and have a quick glance at them and their company's profile. Then when you're back just approach them with great enthusiasm and body language. When you start talking, don't stop it for 10-15 seconds. Be very expressive in your speech. In 15 seconds the person will realize that you're also a person of high value. When they realize this, show your humility and eagerness to learn from them. Talk about how you were impressed by their portfolio and ask them various questions. But, for the\xa0first 15-30 seconds you have to demonstrate the value of yourself by speaking yourself out loudly and in an expressive manner with a laid-back body language, a smiling face, and great eye contact. If you don't have prior information about the person, just start the conversation with what you feel like - eg just ask a question - are you a journalist? then without waiting for the reply or a yes/no reply, self express yourself for the next 15-30 seconds, until they recognize your high value. Then you can resume the conversation in a normal to and fro manner.\xa0"}),(0,a.jsx)("p",{children:"Also, note that as in the exercise you have to change the topic every 20 seconds until you stumble upon a topic that is of interest to both you and the person you're talking to."}),(0,a.jsx)("p",{children:"Later parts of this process will be explained further in the system."}),(0,a.jsx)("h2",{children:"Fallback material"}),(0,a.jsx)("p",{children:"There would be times when irrespective of anything you do or observe, you will fall short of words. For that time you have to prepare a fallback material. For example, you should have material for introduction ready for different occasions. At certain times you may just get blank. Fallback material would come in handy at that time. It is good to have a set of fallback material for the following scenarios:"}),(0,a.jsxs)("ol",{children:[(0,a.jsx)("li",{children:"Introduction (for formal and informal occassions)"}),(0,a.jsx)("li",{children:"What do you do?"}),(0,a.jsx)("li",{children:"What brought you here?"}),(0,a.jsx)("li",{children:"What inspired you to adopt this profession?"}),(0,a.jsx)("li",{children:"What were the challenges that you faced in your journey?"})]}),(0,a.jsx)("p",{children:"You will realize that there is no end to the material that you can use as a fallback. In fact,\xa0that is what every one\xa0of us does. If someone asks us about our favorite movie we don't have to think deeply every time. We already know and remember it. But to accelerate this process you have to deliberate create some basic fallback material and then when you start to practice, you'll have to add more to it. You can add to apps like Anki so that you can remember it better through active recall and spaced repetition. Also, make sure that you don't overexaggerate or write false things in your fallback material. Keep it genuine."}),(0,a.jsx)("h3",{children:"Exercise"}),(0,a.jsx)("p",{children:"Your next exercise is to imagine the events and venues you would visit for networking, like a conference, a professional meetup, professional lunch or dinner, an amusement park, a wedding, or a random place where you're a stranger. How would you answer each of the above questions there? Write them down. Next, imagine five more questions that you think can be asked of you in these situations and write answers to all of them. You have to actively recall these answers along with spaced repetition. Remember to be genuine in your answers and never write false things about yourself."})]})}}},function(e){e.O(0,[774,888,179],(function(){return o=695,e(e.s=o);var o}));var o=e.O();_N_E=o}]);